The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
 Wednesday, July 07, 2004 				 Salim boss in city to talk business
 A STAFF REPORTERCalcutta, July 6: Indonesias Salim Group will discuss investment with the Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee government tomorrow, particularly for developing a township in Howrah. 																								Beni Santoso, the executive director of one of Asias fastest growing conglomerates, is expected to enter into an agreement with the Calcutta Metropolitan Development Authority (CMDA) to develop the satellite township on 390.2 acres in west Howrah. 																								A government official said the agreement is likely to be signed. Santoso is scheduled to reach the city tonight. 																								Though the money the group is likely to pump in has not yet been announced, sources said it could be to the tune of Rs 2,500 crore. 																								The township is likely to be developed in phases, the official said. Representatives of the company who are already in the city were non-committal about the agreement. 																								The Salim chief will meet urban development minister Asok Bhattacharya and finance minister Asim Dasgupta besides the chief minister. 																								Bhattacharya said: Terms and conditions for the agreement have not been set. The Salim group might buy the land in Howrah or the township might be developed in the form of private-public partnership. Nothing is final as yet.
